Expand and simplify completely: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

generations.generations:
First, expand the expression inside the parentheses:
\begin{align*}
x(1+x) + 2x &= x + x^2 + 2x \\
&= 3x + x^2.
\end{align*}
Next, distribute the $-3$ in the second term:
\begin{align*}
-3(x^2 - x + 2) &= -3x^2 + 3x - 6.
\end{align*}
Now, multiply $x$ by each term in the first term:
\begin{align*}
x(3x + x^2) &= 3x^2 + x^3.
\end{align*}
Finally, combine all the terms:
\begin{align*}
3x^2 + x^3 - 3x^2 + 3x - 6 &= x^3 + 3x - 6.
\end{align*}
</reasoning>
<answer>
\boxed{x^3 + 3x - 6}
